# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ecn-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] In routers and switches, **active queue management** (**AQM**) is the policy of dropping packets inside a buffer associated with a network interface controller (NIC) before that buffer becomes full, often with the goal of reducing network congestion or improving end-to-end latency.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] This task is performed by the network scheduler, which for this purpose uses various algorithms such as random early detection (RED), Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN), or controlled delay (CoDel).
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] RFC 7567 recommends active queue management as a best practice.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] An Internet router typically maintains a set of queues, one or more per interface, that hold packets scheduled to go out on that interface.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] Historically, such queues use a *drop-tail* discipline: a packet is put onto the queue if the queue is shorter than its maximum size (measured in packets or in bytes), and dropped otherwise.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] Active queue disciplines drop or mark packets before the queue is full.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] Typically, they operate by maintaining one or more drop/mark probabilities, and occasionally dropping or marking packets according to the probabilities before the queue is full.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] Drop-tail queues have a tendency to penalise bursty flows, and to cause global synchronization between flows.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] By dropping packets probabilistically, AQM disciplines typically avoid both of these issues.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] By providing endpoints with congestion indication before the queue is full, AQM disciplines are able to maintain a shorter queue length than drop-tail queues, which combats bufferbloat and reduces network latency.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] Early AQM disciplines (notably RED and SRED) require careful tuning of their parameters in order to provide good performance.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] These systems are not optimally behaved from a control theory perspective.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] Modern AQM disciplines (ARED, Blue, PI, CoDel, CAKE) are self-tuning, and can be run with their default parameters in most circumstances.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] An active queue management and denial-of-Service (AQM&DoS) simulation platform is established based on the NS-2 simulation code of the RRED algorithm.
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] The AQM&DoS simulation platform can simulate a variety of DoS attacks (Distributed DoS, Spoofing DoS, Low-rate DoS, etc.) and AQM algorithms (RED, RRED, SFB, etc.).
[src:ecn-networking/active-queue-management] It automatically calculates and records the average throughput of normal TCP flows before and after DoS attacks to facilitate the analysis of the impact of DoS attacks on normal TCP flows and AQM algorithms.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] Ethernet is the primary network protocol in data centers for computer-to-computer communications.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] However, Ethernet is designed to be a best-effort network that may experience packet loss when the network or devices are busy.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] Under the end-to-end principle, transport reliability in IP networks is the responsibility of a transport protocol, such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] One area of evolution for Ethernet is to add extensions to the existing protocol suite to provide reliability without requiring the complexity of TCP.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] With the move to 10 Gbit/s and faster transmission rates, there is also a desire for finer granularity in control of bandwidth allocation and to ensure it is used more effectively.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] These enhancements are particularly important to make Ethernet a more viable transport for storage and server cluster traffic.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] A primary motivation is the sensitivity of Fibre Channel over Ethernet to frame loss.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] The higher level goal is to use a single set of Ethernet physical devices or adapters for computers to talk to a storage area network (SAN), local area network (LAN) and InfiniBand fabric.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] DCB aims, for selected traffic, to eliminate loss due to queue overflow (sometimes called **lossless Ethernet**) and to be able to allocate bandwidth on links.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] Essentially, DCB enables, to some extent, the treatment of different priorities as if they were different pipes.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] To meet these goals new standards are being (or have been) developed that either extend the existing set of Ethernet protocols or emulate the connectivity offered by Ethernet protocols.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] Enabling DCB broadly on arbitrary networks with irregular topologies and without special routing may cause deadlocks, large buffering delays, unfairness and head-of-line blocking.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] It was suggested to use DCB to eliminate TCP slow start using the approach of **TCP-Bolt**.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] These new protocols required new hardware and software in both the network and the network interface controller.
[src:ecn-networking/data-center-bridging] Products were being developed by companies such as Avaya, Brocade, Cisco, Dell, EMC, Emulex, HP, Huawei, IBM, and Qlogic.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Conventionally, TCP/IP networks signal congestion by dropping packets.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] When ECN is successfully negotiated, an ECN-aware router may set a mark in the IP header instead of dropping a packet in order to signal impending congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] The receiver of the packet echoes the congestion indication to the sender, which reduces its transmission rate as if it detected a dropped packet.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Rather than responding properly or ignoring the bits, some outdated or faulty network equipment has historically dropped or mangled packets that have ECN bits set.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] As of 2015, measurements suggested that the fraction of web servers on the public Internet for which setting ECN prevents network connections had been reduced to less than 1%.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Passive support has existed in Ubuntu Linux since 12.04 and in Windows Server since 2012.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Passive support in the most popular websites has increased from 8.5% in 2012 to over 70% in May 2017.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Adoption across the Internet now requires clients to actively request ECN.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] In June 2015, Apple announced that ECN will be enabled by default on its supported and future products, to help drive the adoption of ECN signaling industry-wide.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Note that this article describes classic ECN as originally defined; the L4S protocol, published in 2023 and described in RFC 9330, has altered the interpretation of the ECN bits and the expected treatment of traffic compared to classic ECN behavior.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Without ECN, congestion indication echo is achieved indirectly by the detection of lost packets.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] With ECN, the congestion is indicated by setting the ECN field within an IP packet to CE (Congestion Experienced) and is echoed back by the receiver to the transmitter by setting proper bits in the header of the transport protocol.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] For example, when using TCP, the congestion indication is echoed back by setting the ECE bit.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] When both endpoints support ECN they mark their packets with ECT(0) or ECT(1).
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Routers treat the ECT(0) and ECT(1) codepoints as equivalent.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] If the packet traverses an active queue management (AQM) queue (e.g., a queue that uses random early detection (RED)) that is experiencing congestion and the corresponding router supports ECN, it may change the code point to `CE` instead of dropping the packet.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] This act is referred to as *marking* and its purpose is to inform the receiving endpoint of impending congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] At the receiving endpoint, this congestion indication is handled by the upper layer protocol (transport layer protocol) and needs to be echoed back to the transmitting node in order to signal it to reduce its transmission rate.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Because the CE indication can only be handled effectively by an upper layer protocol that supports it, ECN is only used in conjunction with upper layer protocols, such as TCP, that support congestion control and have a method for echoing the CE indication to the transmitting endpoint.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] TCP supports ECN using two flags in the TCP header.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] The first, *ECN-Echo* (ECE) is used to echo back the congestion indication (i.e., signal the sender to reduce the transmission rate).
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] The second, *Congestion Window Reduced* (CWR), to acknowledge that the congestion-indication echoing was received.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Use of ECN on a TCP connection is optional; for ECN to be used, it must be negotiated at connection establishment by including suitable options in the SYN and SYN-ACK segments.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] When ECN has been negotiated on a TCP connection, the sender indicates that IP packets that carry TCP segments of that connection are carrying traffic from an ECN Capable Transport by marking them with an ECT code point.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] This allows intermediate routers that support ECN to mark those IP packets with the CE code point instead of dropping them in order to signal impending congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Upon receiving an IP packet with the *Congestion Experienced* code point, the TCP receiver echoes back this congestion indication using the ECE flag in the TCP header.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] When an endpoint receives a TCP segment with the ECE bit it reduces its congestion window as for a packet drop.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] It then acknowledges the congestion indication by sending a segment with the CWR bit set.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] A node keeps transmitting TCP segments with the ECE bit set until it receives a segment with the CWR bit set.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] To see affected packets with tcpdump, use the filter predicate `(tcp[13] & 0xc0 != 0)`.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Since the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) does not perform congestion control on control packets (pure ACKs, SYN, FIN segments), control packets are usually not marked as ECN-capable.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] A 2009 proposal suggests marking SYN-ACK packets as ECN-capable.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] This improvement, known as ECN+, has been shown to provide dramatic improvements to performance of short-lived TCP connections.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] ECN is also defined for other transport layer protocols that perform congestion control, notably DCCP and Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP).
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] The general principle is similar to TCP, although the details of the on-the-wire encoding differ.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] It is possible to use ECN with protocols layered above UDP.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] However, UDP requires that congestion control be performed by the application, and early UDP based protocols such as DNS did not use ECN.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] More recent UDP based protocols such as QUIC are using ECN for congestion control.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Since ECN is only effective in combination with an active queue management (AQM) policy, the benefits of ECN depend on the precise AQM being used.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] A few observations, however, appear to hold across different AQMs.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] As expected, ECN reduces the number of packets dropped by a TCP connection, which, by avoiding a retransmission, reduces latency and especially jitter.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Effects of ECN on bulk throughput are less clear because modern TCP implementations are fairly good at resending dropped segments in a timely manner when the sender's window is large.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Use of ECN has been found to be detrimental to performance on highly congested networks when using AQM algorithms that never drop packets.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Modern AQM implementations avoid this pitfall by dropping rather than marking packets at very high load.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Many modern implementations of the TCP/IP protocol suite have some support for ECN; however, they usually ship with ECN disabled.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Windows versions since Windows Server 2008 and Windows Vista support ECN for TCP.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Since Windows Server 2012, it is enabled by default in Windows Server versions, because Data Center Transmission Control Protocol (DCTCP) is used.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] In previous Windows versions and non-server versions it is disabled by default.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] ECN support can be enabled using a shell command such as `netsh interface tcp set global ecncapability=enabled`.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] On FreeBSD, ECN for TCP can be configured using the `net.inet.tcp.ecn.enable` sysctl.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] By default, it is enabled only for incoming connections that request it.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] It can also be enabled for all connections or disabled entirely.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] NetBSD 4.0 implements ECN support for TCP; it can be activated through the sysctl interface by setting 1 as value for the sysctl parameter `net.inet.tcp.ecn.enable`.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Likewise, on OpenBSD, the sysctl `net.inet.tcp.ecn` can be used.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Beginning with version 4.1 of the Linux kernel, released in June 2015, the tcp_ecn_fallback mechanism is enabled by default when ECN is enabled (the value of 1).
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] The fallback mechanism attempts ECN connectivity in the initial setup of outgoing connections, with a graceful fallback for transmissions without ECN capability, mitigating issues with ECN-intolerant hosts or firewalls.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Mac OS X 10.5 and 10.6 implement ECN support for TCP.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] It is controlled using the Boolean sysctl variables net.inet.tcp.ecn_negotiate_in and net.inet.tcp.ecn_initiate_out.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] The first variable enables ECN on incoming connections that already have ECN flags set; the second one tries to initiate outgoing connections with ECN enabled.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Both variables default to 0, but can be set to 1 to enable the respective behavior.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] In June 2015, Apple Inc. announced that OS X 10.11 would have ECN turned on by default, but the OS shipped without that default behavior.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] In macOS Sierra, ECN is enabled for half of TCP sessions.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] In June 2015, Apple Inc. announced that iOS 9, its next version of iOS, would support ECN and have it turned on by default.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] As of Solaris 11.4, the default behavior is active.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] ECN usage can be modified via ipadm set-prop -p ecn=active tcp.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Since ECN marking in routers is dependent on some form of active queue management, routers must be configured with a suitable queue discipline in order to perform ECN marking.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Cisco IOS routers perform ECN marking if configured with the WRED queuing discipline since version 12.2(8)T.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Linux routers perform ECN marking if configured with one of the RED or GRED queue disciplines with an explicit *ecn* parameter, by using the sfb discipline, by using the CoDel Fair Queuing (fq_codel) discipline, or the CAKE queuing discipline.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] Modern BSD implementations, such as FreeBSD, NetBSD and OpenBSD, have support for ECN marking in the ALTQ queueing implementation for a number of queuing disciplines, notably RED and Blue.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] FreeBSD 11 included CoDel, PIE, FQ-CoDel and FQ-PIE queuing disciplines implementation in `ipfw` and `dummynet` framework with ECN marking capability.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] DCTCP modifies the TCP receiver to always relay the exact ECN marking of incoming packets at the cost of ignoring a function that is meant to preserve signalling reliability.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] This makes a DCTCP sender vulnerable to loss of ACKs from the receiver, which it has no mechanism to detect or cope with.
[src:ecn-networking/explicit-congestion-notification] As of July 2014, algorithms that provide equivalent or better receiver feedback in a more reliable approach are an active research topic.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Network protocols that use aggressive retransmissions to compensate for packet loss due to congestion can increase congestion, even after the initial load has been reduced to a level that would not normally have induced network congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Such networks exhibit two stable states under the same level of load.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The stable state with low throughput is known as **congestive collapse**.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Networks use **congestion control** and **congestion avoidance** techniques to try to avoid collapse.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] These include: window reduction in TCP, and fair queueing in devices such as routers and network switches.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Other techniques that address congestion include priority schemes, which transmit some packets with higher priority ahead of others and the explicit allocation of network resources to specific flows through the use of admission control.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Network resources are limited, including router processing time and link throughput.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Resource contention may occur on networks in several common circumstances.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] A wireless LAN is easily filled by a single personal computer.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Even on fast computer networks, the backbone can easily be congested by a few servers and client PCs.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Denial-of-service attacks by botnets are capable of filling even the largest Internet backbone network links, generating large-scale network congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] In telephone networks, a mass call event can overwhelm digital telephone circuits, in what can otherwise be defined as a denial-of-service attack.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Congestive collapse (or congestion collapse) is the condition in which congestion prevents or limits useful communication.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Congestion collapse generally occurs at choke points in the network, where incoming traffic exceeds outgoing bandwidth.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Connection points between a local area network and a wide area network are common choke points.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] When a network is in this condition, it settles into a stable state where traffic demand is high but little useful throughput is available, during which packet delay and loss occur and quality of service is extremely poor.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Congestive collapse was identified as a possible problem by 1984.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] It was first observed on the early Internet in October 1986, when the NSFNET phase-I backbone dropped three orders of magnitude from its capacity of 32 kbit/s to 40 bit/s, which continued until end nodes started implementing Van Jacobson and Sally Floyd's congestion control between 1987 and 1988.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] When more packets were sent than could be handled by intermediate routers, the intermediate routers discarded many packets, expecting the endpoints of the network to retransmit the information.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] However, early TCP implementations had poor retransmission behavior.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] When this packet loss occurred, the endpoints sent extra packets that repeated the information lost, doubling the incoming rate.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Congestion control modulates traffic entry into a telecommunications network in order to avoid congestive collapse resulting from oversubscription.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] This is typically accomplished by reducing the rate of packets.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Whereas congestion control prevents senders from overwhelming the *network*, flow control prevents the sender from overwhelming the *receiver*.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The theory of congestion control was pioneered by Frank Kelly, who applied microeconomic theory and convex optimization theory to describe how individuals controlling their own rates can interact to achieve an *optimal* network-wide rate allocation.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Examples of *optimal* rate allocation are max-min fair allocation and Kelly's suggestion of proportionally fair allocation, although many others are possible.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Let $x_{i}$ be the rate of flow i , $c_{l}$ be the capacity of link l , and $r_{li}$ be 1 if flow i uses link l and 0 otherwise.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Let x , c and R be the corresponding vectors and matrix.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Let $U(x)$ be an increasing, strictly concave function, called the utility, which measures how much benefit a user obtains by transmitting at rate x .
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The Lagrange dual of this problem decouples so that each flow sets its own rate, based only on a *price* signaled by the network.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Each link capacity imposes a constraint, which gives rise to a Lagrange multiplier, $p_{l}$ .
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The sum of these multipliers, $y_{i}=\sum _{l}p_{l}r_{li},$ is the price to which the flow responds.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Congestion control then becomes a distributed optimization algorithm.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Many current congestion control algorithms can be modeled in this framework, with $p_{l}$ being either the loss probability or the queueing delay at link l .
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] A major weakness is that it assigns the same price to all flows, while sliding window flow control causes burstiness that causes different flows to observe different loss or delay at a given link.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The correct endpoint behavior is usually to repeat dropped information, but progressively slow the repetition rate.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Provided all endpoints do this, the congestion lifts and the network resumes normal behavior.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Other strategies such as slow start ensure that new connections do not overwhelm the router before congestion detection initiates.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Common router congestion avoidance mechanisms include fair queuing and other scheduling algorithms, and random early detection where packets are randomly dropped as congestion is detected.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] This proactively triggers the endpoints to slow transmission before congestion collapse occurs.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Some end-to-end protocols are designed to behave well under congested conditions; TCP is a well-known example.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The first TCP implementations to handle congestion were described in 1984, but Van Jacobson's inclusion of an open source solution in the Berkeley Standard Distribution UNIX ("BSD") in 1988 first provided good behavior.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Protocols built atop UDP must handle congestion independently.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Protocols that transmit at a fixed rate, independent of congestion, can be problematic.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Real-time streaming protocols, including many Voice over IP protocols, have this property.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Thus, special measures, such as quality of service, must be taken to keep packets from being dropped in the presence of congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Connection-oriented protocols, such as the widely used TCP protocol, watch for packet loss or queuing delay to adjust their transmission rate.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Various network congestion avoidance processes support different trade-offs.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The TCP congestion avoidance algorithm is the primary basis for congestion control on the Internet.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Problems occur when concurrent TCP flows experience tail-drops, especially when bufferbloat is present.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] This delayed packet loss interferes with TCP's automatic congestion avoidance.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] All flows that experience this packet loss begin a TCP retrain at the same moment – this is called TCP global synchronization.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Active queue management (AQM) is the reordering or dropping of network packets inside a transmit buffer that is associated with a network interface controller (NIC).
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] This task is performed by the network scheduler.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] One solution is to use random early detection (RED) on the network equipment's egress queue.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] On networking hardware ports with more than one egress queue, weighted random early detection (WRED) can be used.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] RED indirectly signals TCP sender and receiver by dropping some packets, e.g. when the average queue length is more than a threshold (e.g.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] 50%) and deletes linearly or cubically more packets, up to e.g.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The robust random early detection (RRED) algorithm was proposed to improve the TCP throughput against denial-of-service (DoS) attacks, particularly low-rate denial-of-service (LDoS) attacks.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Experiments confirmed that RED-like algorithms were vulnerable under LDoS attacks due to the oscillating TCP queue size caused by the attacks.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Some network equipment is equipped with ports that can follow and measure each flow and are thereby able to signal a too big bandwidth flow according to some quality of service policy.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] A policy could then divide the bandwidth among all flows by some criteria.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Another approach is to use Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN).
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] ECN is used only when two hosts signal that they want to use it.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] With this method, a protocol bit is used to signal explicit congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] This is better than the indirect congestion notification signaled by packet loss by the RED/WRED algorithms, but it requires support by both hosts.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] When a router receives a packet marked as ECN-capable and the router anticipates congestion, it sets the ECN flag, notifying the sender of congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The sender should respond by decreasing its transmission bandwidth, e.g., by decreasing its sending rate by reducing the TCP window size or by other means.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The L4S protocol is an enhanced version of ECN that allows senders to collaborate with network devices to control congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Congestion avoidance can be achieved efficiently by reducing traffic.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] When an application requests a large file, graphic or web page, it usually advertises a *window* of between 32K and 64K.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] This results in the server sending a full window of data (assuming the file is larger than the window).
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] When many applications simultaneously request downloads, this data can create a congestion point at an upstream provider.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] By reducing the window advertisement, the remote servers send less data, thus reducing the congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Backward ECN (BECN) is another proposed congestion notification mechanism.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] It uses ICMP source quench messages as an IP signaling mechanism to implement a basic ECN mechanism for IP networks, keeping congestion notifications at the IP level and requiring no negotiation between network endpoints.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Effective congestion notifications can be propagated to transport layer protocols, such as TCP and UDP, for the appropriate adjustments.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The protocols that avoid congestive collapse generally assume that data loss is caused by congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] On wired networks, errors during transmission are rare.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] WiFi, 3G and other networks with a radio layer are susceptible to data loss due to interference and may experience poor throughput in some cases.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The TCP connections running over a radio-based physical layer see the data loss and tend to erroneously believe that congestion is occurring.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] The slow-start protocol performs badly for short connections.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Older web browsers created many short-lived connections and opened and closed the connection for each file.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] This kept most connections in the slow start mode.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Initial performance can be poor, and many connections never get out of the slow-start regime, significantly increasing latency.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] To avoid this problem, modern browsers either open multiple connections simultaneously or reuse one connection for all files requested from a particular server.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Admission control is any system that requires devices to receive permission before establishing new network connections.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] If the new connection risks creating congestion, permission can be denied.
[src:ecn-networking/network-congestion] Examples include Contention-Free Transmission Opportunities (CFTXOPs) in the ITU-T G.hn standard for home networking over legacy wiring, Resource Reservation Protocol for IP networks and Stream Reservation Protocol for Ethernet.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, quality of service refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is the ability to provide different priorities to different applications, users, or data flows, or to guarantee a certain level of performance to a data flow.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is particularly important for the transport of traffic with special requirements, including voice over IP and other audio networking techniques, professional video over IP, card-based payments, and real-time computing.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of telephony, quality of service was defined by the ITU in 1994.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service comprises requirements on all the aspects of a connection, such as service response time, loss, signal-to-noise ratio, crosstalk, echo, interrupts, frequency response, loudness levels, and so on.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] A subset of telephony QoS is grade of service (GoS) requirements, which comprises aspects of a connection relating to capacity and coverage of a network, for example, guaranteed maximum blocking probability and outage probability.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, teletraffic engineering refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] For example, a required bit rate, delay, delay variation, packet loss or bit error rates may be guaranteed.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is important for real-time streaming multimedia applications such as voice over IP, multiplayer online games and IPTV, since these often require a fixed bit rate and are delay sensitive.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service is especially important in networks where the capacity is a limited resource, for example, in cellular data communication.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] A network or protocol that supports QoS may agree on a traffic contract with the application software and reserve capacity in the network nodes, for example during a session establishment phase.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] During the session, it may monitor the achieved level of performance, for example, the data rate and delay, and dynamically control scheduling priorities in the network nodes.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] It may release the reserved capacity during a tear down phase.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] A best-effort network or service does not support quality of service.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication over a best-effort network by over-provisioning the capacity so that it is sufficient for the expected peak traffic load.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The resulting absence of network congestion reduces or eliminates the need for QoS mechanisms.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used as a quality measure, with many alternative definitions, rather than referring to the ability to reserve resources.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service sometimes refers to the level of quality of service, i.e. the guaranteed service quality.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] High QoS is often confused with a high level of performance, for example high bit rate, low latency and low bit error rate.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used in application layer services such as telephony and streaming video to describe a metric that reflects or predicts the subjectively experienced quality.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In this context, QoS is the acceptable cumulative effect on subscriber satisfaction of all imperfections affecting the service.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Other terms with similar meaning are the quality of experience (QoE), mean opinion score (MOS), perceptual speech quality measure (PSQM) and perceptual evaluation of video quality (PEVQ).
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] A number of attempts for layer 2 technologies that add QoS tags to the data have gained popularity in the past.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Examples are Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) (a technique between layer 2 and 3).
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Despite these network technologies remaining in use today, this kind of network lost attention after the advent of Ethernet networks.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Today, Ethernet is, by far, the most popular layer 2 technology.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Conventional Internet routers and network switches operate on a best-effort basis.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] This equipment is less expensive, less complex and faster and thus more popular than earlier, more complex technologies that provide QoS mechanisms.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Ethernet optionally uses 802.1p to signal the priority of a frame.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] There were four *type of service* bits and three *precedence* bits originally provided in each IP packet header, but they were not generally respected.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] These bits were later re-defined as Differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] With the advent of IPTV and IP telephony, QoS mechanisms are increasingly available to the end user.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In packet-switched networks, quality of service is affected by various factors, which can be divided into human and technical factors.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Human factors include: stability of service quality, availability of service, waiting times and user information.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Technical factors include: reliability, scalability, effectiveness, maintainability and network congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Due to varying load from disparate users sharing the same network resources, the maximum throughput that can be provided to a certain data stream may be too low for real-time multimedia services.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The network may fail to deliver (*drop*) some packets due to network congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The receiving application may ask for this information to be retransmitted, possibly resulting in congestive collapse or unacceptable delays in the overall transmission.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Sometimes packets are corrupted due to bit errors caused by noise and interference, especially in wireless communications and long copper wires.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The receiver has to detect this, and, just as if the packet was dropped, may ask for this information to be retransmitted.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] It might take a long time for each packet to reach its destination because it gets held up in long queues, or it takes a less direct route to avoid congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In some cases, excessive latency can render an application such as VoIP or online gaming unusable.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Packets from the source will reach the destination with different delays.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] A packet's delay varies with its position in the queues of the routers along the path between source and destination, and this position can vary unpredictably.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Delay variation can be absorbed at the receiver, but in so doing increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] When a collection of related packets is routed through a network, different packets may take different routes, each resulting in a different delay.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The result is that the packets arrive in a different order than they were sent.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] This problem requires special additional protocols for rearranging out-of-order packets.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The reordering process requires additional buffering at the receiver, and, as with packet delay variation, increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] These types of service are called *inelastic*, meaning that they require a certain minimum bit rate and a certain maximum latency to function.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] By contrast, *elastic* applications can take advantage of however much or little bandwidth is available.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Bulk file transfer applications that rely on TCP are generally elastic.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Circuit-switched networks, especially those intended for voice transmission, such as ATM or GSM, have QoS in the core protocol; resources are reserved at each step on the network for the call as it is set up, and there is no need for additional procedures to achieve the required performance.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Shorter data units and built-in QoS were some of the unique selling points of ATM for applications such as video on demand.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication by generously over-provisioning a network so that capacity is based on peak traffic load estimates.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] This approach is simple for networks with predictable peak loads.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] This calculation may need to appreciate demanding applications that can compensate for variations in bandwidth and delay with large receive buffers, which is often possible, for example, in video streaming.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Over-provisioning can be of limited use in the face of transport protocols (such as TCP) that, over time, increase the amount of data placed on the network until all available bandwidth is consumed and packets are dropped.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Such greedy protocols tend to increase latency and packet loss for all users.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The amount of over-provisioning in interior links required to replace QoS depends on the number of users and their traffic demands.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] This limits the usability of over-provisioning.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Newer, more bandwidth-intensive applications and the addition of more users result in the loss of over-provisioned networks.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] This then requires a physical update of the relevant network links, which is an expensive process.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Thus, over-provisioning cannot be blindly assumed on the Internet.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Commercial VoIP services are often competitive with traditional telephone service in terms of call quality, even without QoS mechanisms in use on the user's connection to their ISP and the VoIP provider's connection to a different ISP.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Under high load conditions, however, VoIP may degrade to cell-phone quality or worse.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The mathematics of packet traffic indicates that the network requires just 60% more raw capacity under conservative assumptions.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Unlike single-owner networks, the Internet is a series of exchange points interconnecting private networks.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Hence the Internet's core is owned and managed by a number of different network service providers, not a single entity.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Its behavior is much more unpredictable.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] There are two principal approaches to QoS in modern packet-switched IP networks: a parameterized system based on an exchange of application requirements with the network, and a prioritized system where each packet identifies a desired service level to the network.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Early work used the integrated services (IntServ) philosophy of reserving network resources.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In this model, applications used RSVP to request and reserve resources through a network.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] While IntServ mechanisms do work, it was realized that in a broadband network typical of a larger service provider, Core routers would be required to accept, maintain, and tear down thousands or possibly tens of thousands of reservations.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] It was believed that this approach would not scale with the growth of the Internet, and in any event was antithetical to the end-to-end principle, the notion of designing networks so that core routers do little more than simply switch packets at the highest possible rates.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Under DiffServ, packets are marked either by the traffic sources themselves or by the edge devices where the traffic enters the network.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In response to these markings, routers and switches use various queuing strategies to tailor performance to requirements.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] At the IP layer, DSCP markings use the 6-bit DS field in the IP packet header.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] At the MAC layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q can be used to carry 3 bits of essentially the same information.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Routers and switches supporting DiffServ configure their network scheduler to use multiple queues for packets awaiting transmission from bandwidth-constrained (e.g., wide area) interfaces.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Router vendors provide different capabilities for configuring this behavior, including the number of queues supported, the relative priorities of queues, and the bandwidth reserved for each queue.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In practice, when a packet must be forwarded from an interface with queuing, packets requiring low jitter (e.g., VoIP or videoconferencing) are given priority over packets in other queues.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Typically, some bandwidth is allocated by default to network control packets (such as Internet Control Message Protocol and routing protocols), while best-effort traffic might simply be given whatever bandwidth is left over.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] At the medium access control (MAC) layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q and IEEE 802.1p can be used to distinguish between Ethernet frames and classify them.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Queueing theory models have been developed on performance analysis and QoS for MAC layer protocols.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Cisco IOS NetFlow and the Cisco Class Based QoS (CBQoS) Management Information Base (MIB) are marketed by Cisco Systems.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] One compelling example of the need for QoS on the Internet relates to congestive collapse.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet relies on congestion avoidance protocols, primarily as built into Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), to reduce traffic under conditions that would otherwise lead to congestive collapse.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] QoS applications, such as VoIP and IPTV, require largely constant bitrates and low latency, therefore they cannot use TCP and cannot otherwise reduce their traffic rate to help prevent congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Service-level agreements limit traffic that can be offered to the Internet and thereby enforce traffic shaping that can prevent it from becoming overloaded, and are hence an indispensable part of the Internet's ability to handle a mix of real-time and non-real-time traffic without collapse.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Several QoS mechanisms and schemes exist for IP networking.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] QoS capabilities are available in the following network technologies.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] End-to-end quality of service can require a method of coordinating resource allocation between one autonomous system and another.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for bandwidth reservation as a proposed standard in 1997.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] RSVP is an end-to-end bandwidth reservation and admission control protocol.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] RSVP was not widely adopted due to scalability limitations.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The more scalable traffic engineering version, RSVP-TE, is used in many networks to establish traffic-engineered Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched paths.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The IETF also defined Next Steps in Signaling (NSIS) with QoS signalling as a target.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] NSIS is a development and simplification of RSVP.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Research consortia such as "end-to-end quality of service support over heterogeneous networks" (EuQoS, from 2004 through 2007) and fora such as the IPsphere Forum developed more mechanisms for handshaking QoS invocation from one domain to the next.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] IPsphere defined the Service Structuring Stratum (SSS) signaling bus in order to establish, invoke and (attempt to) assure network services.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] EuQoS conducted experiments to integrate Session Initiation Protocol, Next Steps in Signaling and IPsphere's SSS with an estimated cost of about 15.6 million Euro and published a book.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] A research project Multi Service Access Everywhere (MUSE) defined another QoS concept in a first phase from January 2004 through February 2006, and a second phase from January 2006 through 2007.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Another research project named PlaNetS was proposed for European funding circa 2005.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] A broader European project called "Architecture and design for the future Internet" known as 4WARD had a budget estimated at 23.4 million Euro and was funded from January 2008 through June 2010.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] It included a "Quality of Service Theme" and published a book.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Another European project, called WIDENS (Wireless Deployable Network System), proposed a bandwidth reservation approach for mobile wireless multirate adhoc networks.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Strong cryptography network protocols such as Secure Sockets Layer, I2P, and virtual private networks obscure the data transferred using them.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] As all electronic commerce on the Internet requires the use of such strong cryptography protocols, unilaterally downgrading the performance of encrypted traffic creates an unacceptable hazard for customers.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Yet, encrypted traffic is otherwise unable to undergo deep packet inspection for QoS.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Protocols like ICA and RDP may encapsulate other traffic (e.g. printing, video streaming) with varying requirements that can make optimization difficult.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The Internet2 project found, in 2001, that the QoS protocols were probably not deployable inside its Abilene Network with equipment available at that time.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The group predicted that "logistical, financial, and organizational barriers will block the way toward any bandwidth guarantees" by protocol modifications aimed at QoS.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] They believed that the economics would encourage network providers to deliberately erode the quality of best effort traffic as a way to push customers to higher-priced QoS services.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Instead, they proposed over-provisioning of capacity as more cost-effective at the time.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The Abilene network study was the basis for the testimony of Gary Bachula to the US Senate Commerce Committee's hearing on Network Neutrality in early 2006.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] He expressed the opinion that adding more bandwidth was more effective than any of the various schemes for accomplishing QoS they examined.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Bachula's testimony has been cited by proponents of a law banning quality of service as proof that no legitimate purpose is served by such an offering.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] This argument is dependent on the assumption that over-provisioning isn't a form of QoS and that it is always possible.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Cost and other factors affect the ability of carriers to build and maintain permanently over-provisioned networks.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Mobile cellular service providers may offer mobile QoS to customers just as the wired public switched telephone network service providers and Internet service providers may offer QoS.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] QoS mechanisms are always provided for circuit switched services, and are essential for inelastic services, for example streaming multimedia.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Mobility adds complications to QoS mechanisms.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] A phone call or other session may be interrupted after a handover if the new base station is overloaded.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Unpredictable handovers make it impossible to give an absolute QoS guarantee during the session initiation phase.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Quality of service in the field of telephony was first defined in 1994 in ITU-T Recommendation E.800.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] This definition is very broad, listing 6 primary components: Support, Operability, Accessibility, Retainability, Integrity and Security.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] In 1998 the ITU published a document discussing QoS in the field of data networking.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] X.641 offers a means of developing or enhancing standards related to QoS and provides concepts and terminology that should assist in maintaining the consistency of related standards.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] Some QoS-related IETF Request for Comments (RFC)s are *Baker, Fred; Black, David L.; Nichols, Kathleen; Blake, Steven L.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] (December 1998), *Definition of the Differentiated services Field (DS Field) in the IPv4 and IPv6 Headers*, doi:10.17487/RFC2474, RFC 2474*, and *Braden, Robert T.; Zhang, Lixia; Berson, Steven; Herzog, Shai; Jamin, Sugih (September 1997), Braden, R.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] (ed.), *Resource ReSerVation Protocol (RSVP)*, doi:10.17487/RFC2205, RFC 2205*; both these are discussed above.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The IETF has also published two RFCs giving background on QoS: *Huston, Geoff (November 2000), *Next Steps for the IP QoS Architecture*, doi:10.17487/RFC2990, RFC 2990*, and *Floyd, S.; Kempf, J.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] (ed.), *IAB Concerns Regarding Congestion Control for Voice Traffic in the Internet*, doi:10.17487/RFC3714, RFC 3714*.
[src:ecn-networking/quality-of-service] The document tries to identify applications commonly run over an IP network, groups them into traffic classes, studies the treatment required by these classes from the network, and suggests which of the QoS mechanisms commonly available in routers can be used to implement those treatments.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) uses one of several congestion control algorithms that include various aspects of an additive increase/multiplicative decrease (AIMD) scheme, along with other schemes including slow start and a congestion window (CWND), to achieve congestion avoidance.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The **TCP congestion-avoidance algorithm** is the primary basis for congestion control in the Internet.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Per the end-to-end principle, congestion control is largely a function of internet hosts, not the network itself.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] There are several variations and versions of the algorithm implemented in protocol stacks of operating systems of computers that connect to the Internet.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] To avoid congestive collapse, TCP uses a multi-faceted congestion-control strategy.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] For each connection, TCP maintains a CWND, limiting the total number of unacknowledged packets that may be in transit end-to-end.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] This is somewhat analogous to TCP's sliding window used for flow control.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The additive increase/multiplicative decrease (AIMD) algorithm is a closed-loop control algorithm.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] AIMD combines linear growth of the congestion window with an exponential reduction when congestion occurs.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Multiple flows using AIMD congestion control will eventually converge to use equal amounts of a contended link.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] This is the algorithm that is described in RFC 5681 for the *congestion avoidance* state.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In TCP, the **congestion window** (CWND) is one of the factors that determines the number of bytes that can be sent out at any time.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The congestion window is maintained by the sender and is a means of preventing *a link* between the sender and the receiver from becoming overloaded with too much traffic.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] This should not be confused with the sliding window maintained by the sender, which exists to prevent *the receiver* from becoming overloaded.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The congestion window is calculated by estimating how much congestion there is on the link.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] When a connection is set up, the congestion window, a value maintained independently at each host, is set to a small multiple of the **maximum segment size** (**MSS**) allowed on that connection.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Further variance in the congestion window is dictated by an additive increase/multiplicative decrease (AIMD) approach.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] This means that if all segments are received and the acknowledgments reach the sender on time, some constant is added to the window size.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] A system administrator may adjust the maximum window size limit or adjust the constant added during additive increase, as part of TCP tuning.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The flow of data over a TCP connection is also controlled by the use of the *receive window* advertised by the receiver.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] A sender can send data less than its own congestion window and the *receive window*.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Slow start, defined by RFC 5681, is part of the congestion control strategy used by TCP in conjunction with other algorithms to avoid sending more data than the network is capable of forwarding, that is, to avoid causing network congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Slow start begins initially with a congestion window size (CWND) of 1, 2, 4 or 10 MSS.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The value for the congestion window size can be increased by 1 MSS with each acknowledgment (ACK) received, effectively doubling the window size each RTT.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] If the CWND reaches *ssthresh*, TCP switches to the congestion avoidance algorithm.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It should be increased by up to 1 MSS for each RTT.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] A common formula is that *each new ACK* increases the CWND by *MSS * MSS / CWND.* It increases almost linearly and provides an acceptable approximation.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] If a loss event occurs, TCP assumes that it is due to network congestion and takes steps to reduce the offered load on the network.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] These measures depend on the exact TCP congestion avoidance algorithm used.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] When a TCP sender detects segment loss using the retransmission timer and the given segment has not yet been resent, the value of *ssthresh* must be set to no more than half of the amount of data that has been sent but not yet cumulatively acknowledged or *2 * MSS*, whichever value is greater.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] and slow start begins again from its initial CWND.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] and as the new value for CWND, thus skipping slow start and going directly to the congestion avoidance algorithm.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Slow start assumes that unacknowledged segments are due to network congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] While this is an acceptable assumption for many networks, segments may be lost for other reasons, such as poor data link layer transmission quality.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Thus, slow start can perform poorly in situations with poor reception, such as wireless networks.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The slow start protocol also performs badly for short-lived connections.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Older web browsers would create many consecutive short-lived connections to the web server, and would open and close the connection for each file requested.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] This kept most connections in the slow start mode, which resulted in poor response time.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] To avoid this problem, modern browsers either open multiple connections simultaneously or reuse one connection for all files requested from a particular web server.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Connections, however, cannot be reused for the multiple third-party servers used by websites to implement web advertising, sharing features of social networking services, and counter scripts of web analytics.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] When a sender receives three duplicate acknowledgments, it can be reasonably confident that the segment carrying the data that followed the last in-order byte specified in the acknowledgment was lost.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] A sender with fast retransmit will then retransmit this packet immediately without waiting for its timeout.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] On receipt of the retransmitted segment, the receiver can acknowledge the last in-order byte of data received.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In the above example, this would acknowledge to the end of the payload of the fifth packet.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] There is no need to acknowledge intermediate packets since TCP uses cumulative acknowledgments by default.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The names Reno and Tahoe are the names of releases of the BSD UNIX operating system, and were used to refer to the congestion control algorithms (CCAs) at least as early a 1996 paper by Kevin Fall and Sally Floyd.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Tahoe and Reno algorithms were retrospectively named after the versions or flavors of the 4.3BSD operating system in which each first appeared (which were themselves named after Lake Tahoe and the nearby city of Reno, Nevada).
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The Tahoe algorithm first appeared in 4.3BSD-Tahoe (which was made to support the CCI Power 6/32 "Tahoe" minicomputer), and was later made available to non-AT&T licensees as part of the 4.3BSD Networking Release 1; this ensured its wide distribution and implementation.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Improvements were made in 4.3BSD-Reno and subsequently released to the public as Networking Release 2 and later 4.4BSD-Lite.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In both Tahoe and Reno, if an ACK times out (RTO timeout), slow start is used, and both algorithms reduce the congestion window to 1 MSS.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] TCP New Reno, defined by RFC 6582 (which obsolesces previous definitions in RFC 3782 and RFC 2582), improves retransmission during the fast-recovery phase of TCP Reno.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] During fast recovery, to keep the transmit window full, for every duplicate ACK that is returned, a new unsent packet from the end of the congestion window is sent.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The difference from Reno is that New Reno does not halve ssthresh immediately, which may reduce the window too much if multiple packet losses occur.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It does not exit fast-recovery and reset ssthresh until it acknowledges all of the data.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It uses a variable called *recover* to record how much data needs to be recovered.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] After a retransmit timeout, it records the highest sequence number transmitted in the recover variable and exits the fast recovery procedure.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] If this sequence number is acknowledged, TCP returns to the congestion avoidance state.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] A problem occurs with New Reno when there are no packet losses, but instead, packets are reordered by more than 3 packet sequence numbers.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In this case, New Reno mistakenly enters fast recovery.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] When the reordered packet is delivered, duplicate and needless retransmissions are immediately sent.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] New Reno performs as well as SACK at low packet error rates and substantially outperforms Reno at high error rates.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Until the mid-1990s, all of TCP's set timeouts and measured round-trip delays were based upon only the last transmitted packet in the transmit buffer.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] University of Arizona researchers Larry Peterson and Lawrence Brakmo introduced TCP Vegas, in which timeouts were set and round-trip delays were measured for every packet in the transmit buffer.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In addition, TCP Vegas uses additive increases in the congestion window.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In a 2012 comparison study of various TCP CCAs, TCP Vegas appeared to be the smoothest, followed by TCP CUBIC.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Vegas was not widely deployed outside Peterson's laboratory but was selected as the default congestion control method for DD-WRT firmware v24 SP2.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Hybla aims to eliminate penalties to TCP connections that use high-latency terrestrial or satellite radio links.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Hybla improvements are based on analytical evaluation of the congestion window dynamics.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Binary Increase Congestion control (BIC) is a TCP implementation with an optimized CCA for high-speed networks with high latency, known as long fat networks (LFNs).
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] BIC is used by default in Linux kernels 2.6.8 through 2.6.18.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] CUBIC is a less aggressive and more systematic derivative of BIC, in which the window is a cubic function of time since the last congestion event, with the inflection point set to the window prior to the event.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] CUBIC is used by default in Linux kernels since version 2.6.19.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Agile-SD is a Linux-based CCA that is designed for the real Linux kernel.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It has been evaluated by comparing its performance to Compound TCP (the default CCA in MS Windows) and CUBIC (the default of Linux) using the NS-2 simulator.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It improves the total performance up to 55% in terms of average throughput.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Westwood+ is a sender-only modification of TCP Reno that optimizes the performance of TCP congestion control over both wired and wireless networks.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Westwood+ is based on end-to-end bandwidth estimation to set the congestion window and slow-start threshold after a congestion episode, that is, after three duplicate acknowledgments or a timeout.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The bandwidth is estimated by averaging the rate of returning acknowledgment packets.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In contrast with TCP Reno, which blindly halves the congestion window after three duplicate ACKs, TCP Westwood+ adaptively sets a slow-start threshold and a congestion window that takes into account an estimate of bandwidth available at the time congestion is experienced.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Compared to Reno and New Reno, Westwood+ significantly increases throughput over wireless links and improves fairness in wired networks.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Compound TCP is a Microsoft implementation of TCP that maintains two different congestion windows simultaneously, with the goal of achieving good performance on LFNs while not impairing fairness.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It has been widely deployed in Windows versions since Microsoft Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008 and has been ported to older Microsoft Windows versions as well as Linux.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Proportional Rate Reduction (PRR) is an algorithm designed to improve the accuracy of data sent during recovery.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The algorithm ensures that the window size after recovery is as close as possible to the slow start threshold.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In tests performed by Google, PRR resulted in a 3–10% reduction in average latency and recovery timeouts were reduced by 5%.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] PRR is available in Linux kernels since version 3.2.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Bottleneck Bandwidth and Round-trip propagation time (BBR) is a CCA developed at Google in 2016.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] While most CCAs are loss-based, in that they rely on packet loss to detect congestion and lower rates of transmission, BBR, like TCP Vegas, is model-based.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The algorithm uses the maximum bandwidth and round-trip time at which the network delivered the most recent flight of outbound data packets to build a model of the network.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Each cumulative or selective acknowledgment of packet delivery produces a rate sample that records the amount of data delivered over the time interval between the transmission of a data packet and the acknowledgment of that packet.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] When implemented at YouTube, BBRv1 yielded an average of 4% higher network throughput and up to 14% in some countries.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] BBR has been available for Linux TCP since Linux 4.9.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] BBR version 1 (BBRv1) fairness to non-BBR streams is disputed.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] While Google's presentation shows BBRv1 co-existing well with CUBIC, researchers like Geoff Huston and Hock, Bless and Zitterbart found it unfair to other streams and not scalable.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Hock et al. also found "some severe inherent issues such as increased queuing delays, unfairness, and massive packet loss" in the BBR implementation of Linux 4.9.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] (authors of C2TCP) show that BBRv1 doesn't perform well in dynamic environments such as cellular networks.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] They have also shown that BBR has an unfairness issue.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] For instance, when a CUBIC flow (which is the default TCP implementation in Linux, Android, and MacOS) coexists with a BBR flow in the network, the BBR flow can dominate the CUBIC flow and get the whole link bandwidth from it (see figure 18 in).
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Version 2 attempts to deal with the issue of unfairness when operating alongside loss-based congestion management such as CUBIC.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] In BBRv2 the model used by BBRv1 is augmented to include information about packet loss and information from Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN).
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Whilst BBRv2 may at times have lower throughput than BBRv1 it is generally considered to have better goodput.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Windows 11, version 24H2 and Windows Server 2025 had support for BBRv2, but may not enable it by default.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Version 3 (BBRv3) fixes two bugs in BBRv2 (premature end of bandwidth probing, bandwidth convergence) and performs some performance tuning.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] There is also a variant, termed BBR.Swift, optimized for datacenter-internal links: it uses network_RTT (excluding receiver delay) as the main congestion control signal.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Cellular Controlled Delay TCP (C2TCP) was motivated by the lack of a flexible end-to-end TCP approach that can satisfy various QoS requirements for different applications without requiring any changes in the network devices.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] C2TCP aims to satisfy ultra-low latency and high-bandwidth requirements of applications such as virtual reality, video conferencing, online gaming, vehicular communication systems, etc. in a highly dynamic environment such as current LTE and future 5G cellular networks.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] C2TCP works as an add-on on top of loss-based TCP (e.g., Reno, NewReno, CUBIC, BIC, ...), it is only required to be installed on the server side and makes the average delay of packets bounded to the desired delays set by the applications.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Researchers at NYU showed that C2TCP outperforms the delay and delay-variation performance of various state-of-the-art TCP schemes.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] For instance, they showed that compared to BBR, CUBIC, and Westwood on average, C2TCP decreases the average delay of packets by about 250%, 900%, and 700%, respectively on various cellular network environments.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Elastic-TCP was proposed in February 2019 to increase bandwidth utilization over high-BDP networks in support of cloud computing.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It is a Linux-based CCA that is designed for the Linux kernel.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It is a receiver-side algorithm that employs a loss-delay-based approach using a novel mechanism called a window-correlated weighting function (WWF).
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It has a high level of elasticity to deal with different network characteristics without the need for human tuning.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It has been evaluated by comparing its performance to Compound TCP (the default CCA in MS Windows), CUBIC (the default for Linux) and TCP-BBR (the default of Linux 4.9 used by Google) using the NS-2 simulator and testbed.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Elastic-TCP significantly improves the total performance in terms of average throughput, loss ratio, and delay.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Soheil Abbasloo et al. proposed NATCP (Network-Assisted TCP), a controversial TCP design targeting multi-access edge computing (MEC).
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The key idea of NATCP is that if the characteristics of the network were known beforehand, TCP would have been designed differently.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Therefore, NATCP employs the available features and properties in the current MEC-based cellular architectures to push the performance of TCP close to the optimal performance.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] NATCP uses out-of-band feedback from the network to the servers located nearby.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The feedback from the network, which includes the capacity of the cellular access link and the minimum RTT of the network, guides the servers to adjust their sending rates.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] As preliminary results show, NATCP outperforms the state-of-the-art TCP schemes.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] TCP New Reno was the most commonly implemented algorithm, SACK support is very common and is an extension to Reno/New Reno.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Most others are competing proposals that still need evaluation.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Starting with 2.6.8 the Linux kernel switched the default implementation from New Reno to BIC.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] The default implementation was again changed to CUBIC in the 2.6.19 version.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] FreeBSD from version 14.X onwards also uses CUBIC as the default algorithm.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] However, FreeBSD supports a number of other choices.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] When the per-flow product of bandwidth and latency increases, regardless of the queuing scheme, TCP becomes inefficient and prone to instability.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] This becomes increasingly important as the Internet evolves to incorporate very high-bandwidth optical links.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Interactive (iTCP) allows applications to subscribe to TCP events and respond accordingly, enabling various functional extensions to TCP from outside TCP layer.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Most TCP congestion schemes work internally. iTCP additionally enables advanced applications to directly participate in congestion control, such as to control the source generation rate.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Zeta-TCP detects congestion from both latency and loss rate measures.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] To maximize the goodput, Zeta-TCP applies different congestion window backoff strategies based on the likelihood of congestion.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] It also has other improvements to accurately detect packet losses, avoiding retransmission timeout, and accelerate and control the inbound (download) traffic.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] CCAs may be classified in relation to network awareness, meaning the extent to which these algorithms are aware of the state of the network.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] This consist of three primary categories: black box, grey box, and green box.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Black box algorithms offer blind methods of congestion control.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] They operate only on the binary feedback received upon congestion and do not assume any knowledge concerning the state of the networks which they manage.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Grey box algorithms use time-based measurements, such as RTT variation and rate of packet arrival, in order to obtain measurements and estimations of bandwidth, flow contention, and other knowledge of network conditions.
[src:ecn-networking/tcp-congestion-control] Green box algorithms offer bimodal methods of congestion control that measure the fair share of total bandwidth that should be allocated for each flow, at any point, during the system's execution.
